05546nam a22007095i 9780292792876DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212010txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927928767 a10.7560/7227672doi  a(DE-B1597)587195  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 7aSOC0000002bisacsh04a937/.71 aMorter, Jon, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Chora of Croton 1 :bThe Neolithic Settlement at Capo Alfiere /cJon Morter; ed. by John Robb. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©2010  a1 online resource (316 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tSpecial Acknowledgments -- tAcknowledgments -- tForeword -- tIntroduction -- tI. The Neolithic Settlement at Capo Alfiere -- t1 The Site of Capo Alfiere -- t2 Cultural Setting -- t3 Environmental Setting -- t4 History of Research at Capo Alfiere -- t5 Stratigraphy Interpreted -- t6 Architectural and Structural Features -- t7 The Ceramic Assemblage -- t8 Stone Tools -- t9 Miscellaneous Objects -- t10 Organic Remains -- t11 Local Comparative Material -- t12 Conclusions and Future Directions -- tII. Environment and Economy -- t13 Geomorphology -- t14 Faunal Analysis: Bones from Animals of Economic Importance -- t15 Faunal Analysis: Small Mammalian Bones -- t16 Archaeobotany -- tIII. Object Studies -- t17 Bone Artifacts -- t18 Thin Sections (Notes on an Eastern Calabrian Assemblage in the Stentinello Tradition) -- t19 Tokens (Four Pieces of Clay: “Tokens” from Capo Alfiere, Calabria) -- tCatalog of Ceramic, Lithic, and Other Finds -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFrom 1974 to the present, the Institute of Classical Archaeology (ICA) at the University of Texas at Austin has carried out archaeological excavations and surveys in ancient territories (chorae) in southern Italy. This wide-ranging investigation, which covers a large number of sites and a time period ranging from prehistory to the Middle Ages, has unearthed a wealth of new information about ancient rural economies and cultures in the region. These discoveries will be published in two multivolume series (Metaponto and Croton). This volume on the Neolithic settlement at Capo Alfiere is the first in the Croton series. The Chora of Croton 1 reports the excavation results of a remarkable Neolithic site at Capo Alfiere on the Ionian coast. Capo Alfiere is one of a very few early inhabitation sites in this area to have been excavated extensively, with a full team of scientific specialists providing interdisciplinary studies on early farming and animal husbandry. It provides comprehensive documentation of the economy, material culture, and way of life in the central Mediterranean in the sixth and fifth millennia BC. Most notable are the remains of a wattle-and-daub hut enclosed within a massive stone wall. Unique for this area, this well-preserved structure may have been used for special purposes such as ritual, as well as for habitation. The presence of Stentinello wares shows that the range of this pottery type extended further east than previously thought and casts new light on the development of ceramics in the area.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aColeman Carter, Joseph, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCostantini Biasini, Loredana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCostantini, Lorenzo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFolk, Robert L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGál, Erika, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relato